entry.title: Disable multi-process app-bound encryption tests for component builds
entry.content:
As part of testing app-bound encryption, the tests use

temporary executables with various names, path locations, and

attributes (such as digital signature) to verify different

behaviors in the identity capture part of the elevation service.



However, in component builds, the test executable has many DLL

dependencies as part of the build, meaning it cannot easily be

hermetically moved to different locations on disk to truly

test these behaviors.



Because of this, this CL disables the multi-process app-bound

encryption tests on component builds.



Since component builds are not shipped, this does not affect

test coverage for production builds, which are still fully

covered by all the tests.



BUG=324456506

entry.title: Ignore drag events while waiting to exit a nested run loop.
entry.content:
Background: When dragging tabs into another window, TabDragController exits the nested run loop that was handling the window drag and resumes handling the drag session within the original, parent run loop. But that is not an atomic event - it must return control and wait for the nested run loop to exit. If any additional calls into TabDragController::Drag happen between TabDragController asking to exit the run loop and that nested run loop actually exiting, TabDragController could do unexpected things while handling those events. Notably, if it tried to start another nested run loop, this would CHECK.



This CL extends TabDragController's DragState state enum to explicitly model this interval with a `kWaitingToExitRunLoop` state, so it can ignore calls to Drag during this interval.



It's worth noting that some platforms (Chrome OS and Linux) will use this new state, and others (Windows and Mac) will not because they instead already use the kWaitingToDragTabs state during the same interval. These are modeled separately because they correspond to very different underlying states for the drag session - see the comments on the enum values for details.

entry.title: Convert existing orientation-event web tests to test_driver
entry.content:
The purpose of this change is to stop using the JS mocks-based

implementation and start using WebDriver and virtual sensors for

interoperability. WebDriver commands for Generic Sensor are defined in

https://www.w3.org/TR/generic-sensor/#automation, and the Device

Orientation-specific parts are defined in

https://www.w3.org/TR/orientation-event/#automation.



The TestHelper class was created to simplify tests. It takes care of

creating and removing the backing virtual sensors for each event type,

and handling permissions. It also contains some previously free

functions that now depend on virtual sensors (such as setData()).

More generic functions which do not need information saved in TestHelper

remain untouched in the same orientation-event-helpers.js file.



Care has been taken to avoid changing the values and the order of the

calls in the tests as much as possible. Notes about some cases where it

was not possible:

1. Currently it is not possible to set individual values to null because

the parsing algorithms used by

https://w3c.github.io/sensors/#update-virtual-sensor-reading-command

always expect numbers. This affected null-values.https.html test.

2. "deviceorientation" and "deviceorientationabsolute" events whose

readings don't differ from the previous one by a certain amount are

ignored per spec (https://www.w3.org/TR/orientation-event/#significant-change-in-orientation).

Because of this requirement second test values needed to be changed

in add-listener-from-callback.https.html test for Device Orientation.

3. motion/add-listener-from-callback.https.html: The second listener is

added before the first one is removed to avoid needlessly stopping

the sensor.

entry.title: [Test Automation] Better error message when step fails on element hidden
entry.content:
Many tests refer to the same UI element for one or more subsequent

steps. In these cases (as well as when this behavior is explicitly set),

if the element becomes hidden in the middle of the sequence, a step will

fail.



This failure can be confusing, as it can be due to bad UI behavior, a

timeout, etc. Often, it can be a side-effect of the next step never

happening. However, up to this point, only the failed step was

included in the error message.



This CL changes the error message to look more like this:



Interactive test failed on step 1 (WaitForShow()) with reason

kElementHiddenDuringStep; step type kShown; id kTestId1;

element 0x7fff72b298c8; while waiting for:

{ step 2 (WaitForActivate()); id kTestId1 }



The bit at the end - "while waiting for: { ... }" - is the new text.



This should make it at least a little clearer for people who are trying

to debug their test failures.

entry.title: [Android TRM] Refactor to prepare for Magic Stack integration.
entry.content:
Currently the Tab Resumption Module only appears on the NTP as a

standalone module. We'd like to integrate it into the Magic Stack, so it

can appear alongside other modules, and show up on the Start Surface as

well.



This CL restructures the code to make the above integration easier.

There is no feature changes. Details:

* Remove DATA_PROVIDER from Model: TabResumptionDataProvider is now

directly passed to Mediator by CTOR (but still owned by Coordinator).

* Add TITLE to Model:

* This makes title accessible by Coordinator, to prepare for usage by

overridden ModuleProvider.getModuleTitle() in Coordinator.

* Computed (moved from View) and set by Mediator on suggestion fetch.

* Computation needs Resources. Before we got it from View. Now we

get it from Context (more on this later).

* Binds to newly added setTitle() in View.

* Render triggering in View:

* Rendering needs {URL_IMAGE_PROVIDER, CLICK_CALLBACK,

SUGGESTION_BUNDLE}. Previously the first 2 were set in Coordinator

CTOR, which binds to View setters. Then SUGGESTION_BUNDLE is bound

to View.setSuggestionBundleThenRender(), which then renders,

assuming all data are available.

* The assumption breaks down for Magic Stack, which can set all

properties in one setting in arbitrary order.

* To fix: Rename the above to setSuggestionBundle(), and move

rendering calls to renderIfReady(), which is called when setting

all 3 properties, but only actually renders when all required data

{|mUrlImageProvider|, |mClickCallback|, |mBundle|} are available

(noting that |mBundle| can be null).

* Mediator:

* Add CTOR param |context|: Used to compute title (referred to above).

* Add CTOR param |dataProvider|: For direct usage.

* Add CTOR params {|urlImageProvider|, |suggestionClickCallback|}, to

be assigned into Model. This moves business logic from Coordinator,

and improves testing.

* Rename reload() to loadModule().

* Coordinator:

* Still own data / image providers.

* Duplicate reload() to showModule(), which will be a Magic Stack

override. Keeping reload() for semantic accuracy.



Test details:

* TabResumptionModuleMediatorTest:

* Replace Coordinator usage with direct Mediator usage, now that we

can pass in more CTOR params.

* Stop test that relies on bind() (now that Coordinator is not used).

Specifically, remove URL image load (covered by View test) tests

and simulated clicks (moved to View test).

* Test title (singular and plural) via TITLE in Model.

* TabResumptionModuleViewUnitTest:

* Add 1 test: testSetTitle(), to test title assignment in View.

* testRender{Single,Double}(): Remove title test, since TITLE is now

assigned by Mediator via Model, and tested there.

* Add tile click tests, now using performClick().

entry.title: [A11y] Refactors Dictation's macros to common/
entry.content:
This will allow other features, like FaceGaze, to use macros

for action fulfillment. We can add more macro types for all

features that need action fulfillment here, and eventually move

some of that fulfillment logic as well, so that multiple types

of features can do actions like "undo", "right click", etc.



For starters, just Dictation and FaceGaze can share the Macro

concept, but eventually Switch Access and ChromeVox could change

the way they perform actions to match this setup.



This change moves most of Dictation's macros to common/

except for list_commands, which is currently pretty specific

to Dictation. It also renames "stop listening" to "toggle

dictation", since other features (like ChromeVox, FaceGaze)

may wish to toggle dictation in the same way.



See one-pager at go/cros-a11y-fulfillment-vs-triggers.

entry.title: [views_ax] Introducing ViewsAXCompletedAttributes
entry.content:
This CL introduces a class intended to keep track of the

properties that have already been migrated from the old system

of computing AXNodeData for Views (pull), to the new system (push).

This will help ensure that new Views don't use the old system for

attributes that have already been migrated, since the migration

will take some time. Once the migration is complete, this class

will be removed.



This CL also introduced a function that will merge the AXNodeData

that is computed through the old system, with the AXNodeData that

exists from the new system, so that both systems can coexist while

the migration takes place.



Lastly, this CL also adds a new AXNodeData member to

ViewAccessibility. This will be where the properties set through the

new system are stored. While this means that we have two AXNodeData

members living in ViewAccessibility, this is only temporary,

as override_data_ will be removed once the migration is done.

entry.title: Refactoring in advance of supporting overloaded operator()()s.
entry.content:
* Rename `IsCallableObject` to `HasNonOverloadedCallOp`. This is more

accurate (functors with overloaded call ops are callable; there are

also callable objects that do not have an operator()() at all). It is

also more parallel with adding a `HasOverloadedCallOp` later.

* Pass the traits (or bools from them) along to various templates

instead of repeatedly rederiving them. This makes changing the

signature of `FunctorTraits` significantly more feasible, and should

improve compile times as well.

* Provide better error handling for binding to non-invocable functors.

For now this triggers on (at least) all functors with overloaded

entry.title: device orientation: Wait for null event in device-orientation-success.js
entry.content:
The test was flaky on multiple platforms because there was a window

between removeEmulationDomainSensorOverride() and

firstOrientationOverride() during which the call to

setSensorOverrideEnabled(false, ...) with an active event listener would

cause it to fire an event with all-null attributes.



The round() function used in the handler did not support null objects,

so the entire TypeError call stack was logged and would sometimes be

caught by the call to ConsoleTestRunner.waitUntilNthMessageReceived() in

firstOrientationOverride(). This led to all following console sniffing

expectations to be off-by-one.



Remove the flakiness by always expecting the null event caused by the

removal of the sensor backing the active DeviceOrientationEventPump in

removeEmulationDomainSensorOverride().

entry.title: [bookmarks] Refactor BookmarkModel::Load() signature
entry.content:
No behavioral changes, pure refactoring to simplify the signature and

avoid accidental misuse outside iOS.



The case where, before this patch, StorageType::kAccount was used as

input to BookmarkModel::Load() was very rare, tailored to iOS, and

somewhat incompatible with the existence of feature toggles, namely

`syncer::kEnableBookmarkFoldersForAccountStorage`.



After all, BookmarkModel APIs have evolved recently to directly support

account bookmarks (without the need for another BookmarkModel instance),

starting with https://crrev.com/c/4952185. The historical iOS setup

where account bookmarks are loaded or "mapped" to regular,

local-or-syncable bookmarks is best achieved with a dedicated API that

shouldn't be adopted outside iOS.

entry.title: oak birch: revamp bar to have tight bounds
entry.content:
Current bar horrizontally occupies the whole space even the content

does not. This cl makes the bounds tight with following changes:

1. Change the bar from 3 level nested box layout to 2 levels such

that the bar is the direct parent of chip rows.

2. Add a function called UpdateAvailableSpace to ask the bar

container to provide the available space and the bar will

relayout according to the space.

3. Add a function called GetContainerPaddings which returns the

paddings to the bar container to calculate the available space.

4. The bar will only relayout when adding and removing chips, and

available space changed.

The final effects are shown in the bug comment.
